{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":50574,"duration_api_ms":50540,"num_turns":11,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"c59db672-2501-457f-8438-0a6e25a38564","total_cost_usd":0.33900925000000004,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":30627,"cache_read_input_tokens":191811,"output_tokens":2066,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":30627,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":2066,"cacheReadInputTokens":191811,"cacheCreationInputTokens":30627,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.33900925000000004,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Evaluated three amendments against the actual code. Amendment fr-16-8d96fcd0 identifies a real but low-severity diagnostic issue that is a valid improvement. Amendment fr-16-c6b392f9 mischaracterizes the implementation as a regression when the code deliberately and correctly deviates from Issue 3 for safety reasons, with tests that accurately document the actual behavior. Amendment fr-16-ec78c103 identifies a real control-flow gap in the run_id update path where an early error return prevents fallthrough to the terminal replay matcher.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-16-8d96fcd0","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment correctly identifies that the contract violation at fs.rs:2838-2844 logs an error but returns None, causing the caller to surface a misleading CorruptRecord error ('no matching task run') instead of an error describing the actual programmer bug (run_id supplied without started_at). Changing the return type to AppResult<Option<usize>> would make the contract violation self-describing in error reports, aiding future debugging. The current behavior technically works — it prevents the unsafe bypass and does result in an error — but the error message is misleading and could waste significant debugging time if triggered. This is a legitimate robustness improvement."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-c6b392f9","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment claims Issue 3 is 'unimplemented' and tests 'mask the regression,' but reading the actual code tells a different story. The code at fs.rs:2608-2622 contains a lengthy, deliberate comment explaining WHY legacy entries (snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation == None) are not backfilled: the state is ambiguous between 'created before any plan existed' and 'legacy entry from older code.' The safe_plan_hash_backfill function at fs.rs:2583-2622 DOES backfill when snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation is Some and the snapshot hasn't evolved (line 2600-2601), which covers the primary case correctly. The tests at service.rs:4727-4817 assert that plan_hash is None at start time (correct — dispatch race) and is backfilled at completion when the snapshot is unchanged (correct — safe backfill). The test at service.rs:5274-5285 explicitly documents this as a 'deliberate deviation from Issue 3 acceptance criteria,' asserting the None-provenance skip. The tests at 5635-5844 test both the fill and skip paths of safe_plan_hash_backfill. The tests accurately document and verify the actual implemented behavior — they are not masking a regression, they are asserting a deliberate safety-first deviation. The new-entry path at fs.rs:3040-3058 records snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation for provenance while leaving plan_hash None to avoid the dispatch-v1/snapshot-v2 race, which is the correct design choice documented in the code comments."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-ec78c103","decision":"accept","rationale":"The amendment identifies a real control-flow issue. At fs.rs:3165-3176, when there is a single open runless row whose started_at does NOT match the request, the code immediately returns a CorruptRecord error. It never falls through to the terminal replay matcher (fs.rs:3127-3152) to check if a completed row with the matching started_at exists. This means: if bead B was started (runless, started_at=T1), then retried (started_at=T2, creating a new open entry), and then the original T1 attempt actually completed but crashed before persisting, a replay of that T1 completion with a run_id would hit the T2 open runless row, see started_at mismatch, and error out — even though a terminal row at T1 might exist and be the correct replay target. The fix should allow fallthrough to the terminal replay path when the open runless match fails on started_at, consistent with the partial-write repair contract described at service.rs:527-530."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"2c6fe449-86a8-471c-b396-6678fa297a1a"}
